node.text:
This week, instead of sipping, we’re snacking. Contributing editor Sean Flynn (@travelingnewyorker) is back in Riviera Nayarit, Mexico at One&Only Mandarina (@oomandarina) cooking with Executive Chef Olivier Deboise (@olideboise). Chef’s Fire-Roasted Gratinated Oysters are sure to be a hit at your next summer party.
.
Ingredients:
½ dozen oysters
1 ½ oz butter
1 ½ oz aged goat cheddar
½ tsp shallots, diced
½ tsp Serrano chili, chopped
½ tsp epazote, julienned
Zest of 1 lemon
Zest of 1 lime 
.
Top each oyster with ¼ oz of butter and divide the chopped ingredients, lemon zest, and lime zest among the oysters. Top with grated aged goat cheddar. Grill over a medium to low flame for three to four minutes and brûlée for one and a half minutes. Serve hot.

node.title: These Fire-Roasted Oysters Are the Perfect Summer Appetizer

node.text: Next up on Sipping With, Sean (@travelingnewyorker) visits One&Only Mandarina (@oomandarina) in beautiful Riviera Nayarit, Mexico, where Mixologist Ivan Aguilar shows us how to make one of his favorite cocktails. Of course, no trip to Mexico is complete without tequila, so naturally, that’s our spirit of choice for this episode. In fact, Ivan shows us that tequila can be used to add a twist to cocktails that traditionally use other liquors. We hope you’ll follow along and sip with us at home. Cheers!

node.title: Calling All Tequila Lovers, This Cocktail Could Become Your New Favorite

Cheers!

node.title: Learn How One of the Best Hotels in NYC Makes Its Signature Margarita

node.text: In this new video series, Walk With T+L, we'll be taking you on some of the best walking tours across the globe. On this episode: the island of Amorgos, Greece. Tour by @_thebluewalk

node.text:
This week on Behind the Views: Joann Pai (@sliceofpai). Joann started out as a food photographer, but then, an Oregon tourism organization took a chance on her and sent her on a trip to photograph the state. “Before that trip, most of my photos were still life and shot indoors, so it was a big change for me,” she recently shared with T+L. “I remember how challenging, yet exhilarating, it was to have little control over outdoor elements I never had to think about before.” Fast forward to 2021, and Joann is a now full-time food and travel photographer based in Paris.
.
When asked about her approach to photography, she says, “On a personal level, I try to capture whatever draws me to tell its story, whether it’s food, architecture, people. If the conditions aren’t ideal — there’s bad lighting, it’s too crowded — I usually plan to return at a different time. If I’m scouting for work purposes, I research in advance to see what’s been done and try to shoot from a different perspective.”
.
Joann’s advice for aspiring photographers: “These days there’s just so much content out there that it’s hard not to let it influence your work. I struggle a lot with that myself. Try to take the time to find your voice and tell your own story through your images.” 
.

node.text: T+L Editor in Chief @jacquigiff was live from Charleston, South Carolina to celebrate the launch of the 2021 World’s Best Awards! Congrats to @explorecharleston for winning Best City in the U.S. and to all of the winners. 🎉

node.text:
The best islands in the world, according to T+L readers, are the kind of Instagram-perfect destinations that travelers fantasize about on winter evenings: dreamy, sun-drenched landscapes surrounded by the bluest waters. And since there’s an island destination for everyone, what constitutes “paradise” likely boils down to specific interests — history, culture, heart-pumping adventure, or something else entirely.
.
At the link in bio, get the full list of the Top 25 Islands in the World, as chosen by T+L readers in this year’s World’s Best Awards survey.

node.text:
Although many of us were grounded for much of 2020, in our hearts, we remained global citizens. Travel + Leisure readers know that adventures never cease, even when we remain close to home — and an excellent hotel can still put a smile on your face, especially when the world feels tumultuous.
.
From the Caribbean to Southeast Asia, from Africa to South America, this year’s top 100 winners span the globe and include city skyscrapers, jungle glamping, palace resorts, luxe safari lodges, and seaside hideaways. But top-notch service, premier locations, and over-the-top amenities connect the winners and ensure they rise above the rest.
.
At the link in bio, get the full list of the Top 100 Hotels in the World, as chosen by T+L readers in this year’s World’s Best Awards survey.

node.text:
What attracts travelers to certain cities around the world? Is it new Michelin-starred restaurants? Generations-old cultural heritage? Proximity to geographic wonders of the world? Unsurprisingly, when it comes to determining the best cities in the world, it’s all of the above for our readers.
.

node.text:
From the rocky cliffs of Malibu to the seashore of Miami Beach, the settings that lay claim to the best resort hotels in the continental United States are as varied and dynamic as the readers of Travel + Leisure.
.
And while the hotels that emerged as voter favorites are also incredibly diverse in size and style, there’s one major takeaway that unites them: They’ve all provided unparalleled hospitality, even amid the most difficult of circumstances.
.
At the link in bio, get the full list of the Top 15 Resort Hotels in the Continental U.S., as chosen by T+L readers in this year’s World’s Best Awards survey.

node.text:
As travelers sought outlets for their wanderlust over the past year, they turned to their own backyards, stretching the definition of “drive market” perhaps further than it’s gone before. Southern cities continue to steal the hearts of T+L readers, thanks to the wonderful mix of warm hospitality, approachable size, excellent food, and striking architecture.
.
